Clearly, that requires the
participation of
the regime, with the support of
their allies.

11:11.037 --> 11:15.341 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: But Haley
seemed to suggest
otherwise on CNN's "STATE OF THE
UNION."

11:15.375 --> 11:17.744 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NIKKI HALEY, U.S. Ambassador to
the United
Nations: There's not any sort of
option where

11:17.777 --> 11:20.613 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a political solution is going to
happen with
Assad at the head of the regime.

11:20.647 --> 11:25.885 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, regime change is something
that we think
is going to happen, because all
of the parties

11:25.919 --> 11:29.188 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are going to see that Assad is
not the leader
that needs to be taking place
for Syria.

11:29.222 --> 11:33.493 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: Today in
Washington, White
House Press Secretary Sean
Spicer tried to

11:33.526 --> 11:35.261 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
square the two statements.

11:35.295 --> 11:39.566 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SEAN SPICER, White House Press
Secretary:
I can't imagine a stable and
peaceful Syria

11:39.599 --> 11:42.402 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
where Bashar al-Assad is in
power.

11:42.435 --> 11:45.772 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And there can be a multipronged
approach.

11:45.805 --> 11:50.843 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We are ensuring that ISIS is
contained and
there is a de-escalation of the
proliferation

11:50.877 --> 11:57.250 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of chemical weapons at the same
time creating
the environment for a change in
leadership.

11:57.283 --> 12:03.222 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: Spicer also
raised the possibility
of U.S. military action against
Assad for

12:03.256 --> 12:04.991 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
use of conventional weapons.

12:05.024 --> 12:10.697 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SEAN SPICER: If you gas a baby,
if you put
a barrel bomb into innocent
people, I think

12:10.730 --> 12:13.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you can -- you will see a
response from this
president.

12:13.633 --> 12:18.004 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: Tillerson, who
has charged
that Syria's principal backer,
Russia, was

12:18.037 --> 12:24.010 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
either -- quote -- "complicit or
simply incompetent"
in Syria's use of chemical
weapons, heads

12:24.043 --> 12:26.512 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to Moscow for meetings
Wednesday.

12:26.546 --> 12:32.518 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He will meet with Foreign
Minister Sergei
Lavrov, but not, the Kremlin
announced today,

12:32.552 --> 12:34.988 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
with President Vladimir Putin.

12:35.021 --> 12:37.724 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm
Margaret Warner.

12:37.757 --> 12:42.762 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: In a statement
this afternoon,
U.S. Defense Secretary James
Mattis said Friday's

12:42.795 --> 12:48.768 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
U.S. missile strike damaged or
destroyed 20
percent of Syria's operational
aircraft, and

12:48.801 --> 12:52.972 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that jets could no longer refuel
or rearm
at that base.

12:53.006 --> 12:58.578 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For more on U.S. options in
Syria, relations
with Russia and the ongoing
crisis with North

12:58.611 --> 13:02.315 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Korea, I sat down a short time
ago with retired
Admiral Mike Mullen.

13:02.348 --> 13:07.520 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He served as chairman of the
Joint Chiefs
of Staff from 2007 to 2011.

13:07.553 --> 13:09.756 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Syria, first of all.

13:09.789 --> 13:12.825 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Was the U.S. strike on that
airfield justified?

13:12.859 --> 13:14.327 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
ADM.

13:14.360 --> 13:16.129 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MICHAEL MULLEN, Former Joints
Chiefs Chairman:
I think it was justified.

13:16.162 --> 13:20.099 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think it sent a pretty strong
message that
the use of chemical weapons,
which are banned

13:20.133 --> 13:23.603 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
globally, is not to be
tolerated.

13:23.636 --> 13:25.938 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I think that was the main
message.

13:25.972 --> 13:31.377 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
What has been a little
surprising to me, anyway,
is to find out through media
that there actually

13:31.411 --> 13:35.081 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
have been several chemical
attacks recently.

13:35.114 --> 13:40.753 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, with some belief on my
part, and I think
a lot of people, that we thought
we got rid

13:40.787 --> 13:46.859 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of the chemical weapons with the
regime that
President Obama and President
Putin put in

13:46.893 --> 13:48.795 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
place.

13:48.828 --> 13:51.831 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's a bit of a surprise, but
I think we
have to send the message that
this is unacceptable.

13:51.864 --> 13:54.534 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Do you think that
message has
been received?

13:54.567 --> 13:55.768 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
What do you think this
accomplished?

13:55.802 --> 13:56.969 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
ADM.

13:57.003 --> 13:58.571 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MICHAEL MULLEN: I think the
message has been
received.

13:58.604 --> 14:00.773 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And it was really focused on
that.

14:00.807 --> 14:06.412 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I certainly have seen the
discussion that,
after the fact, that that air
base was back

14:06.446 --> 14:08.214 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in operations.

14:08.247 --> 14:11.584 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That didn't surprise me, but I
thought it
was proportional, which I think
is important.

14:11.617 --> 14:16.222 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was focused on the air force,
which has
been barrel bombing its people,
you know,

14:16.255 --> 14:20.193 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for some time, and, in that
regard, a pretty
strong message.

14:20.226 --> 14:26.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Will it, in fact, be absorbed by
Assad and
others?

14:26.866 --> 14:28.067 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I don't know.

14:28.101 --> 14:29.802 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think that's what we're going
to have to
wait and see.

14:29.836 --> 14:33.206 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Do you think it
means that
if Assad uses chemical weapons
again, the

14:33.239 --> 14:34.540 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
U.S. will strike again?

14:34.574 --> 14:35.641 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
ADM.

14:35.675 --> 14:37.577 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MICHAEL MULLEN: I don't know the
answer to
that.

14:37.610 --> 14:41.380 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Certainly, you know, from where
I sit, there's
an expectation that, if he
continues, obviously,

14:41.414 --> 14:44.083 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
he will continue to pay a price
for that.

14:44.117 --> 14:47.420 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And so we will see.

14:47.453 --> 14:52.925 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's just such a tragedy to see
what he has
done to his own countrymen, you
know, the

14:52.959 --> 14:58.631 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
civilians, the women, the
children, and just
the visible images of that
chemical strike.

14:58.664 --> 15:03.369 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I don't think -- I think, in the
long run,
he loses if he continues to do
that.

15:03.402 --> 15:06.205 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
How that happens, what the --
I'm not really
sure.

15:06.239 --> 15:11.911 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, is it clear
to you, Admiral
Mullen, what the priority of the
Trump administration

15:11.944 --> 15:13.279 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
is now toward Syria?

15:13.312 --> 15:17.416 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Is it mainly to continue the
fight against
ISIS?

15:17.450 --> 15:19.519 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Is it more now against President
Assad?

15:19.552 --> 15:21.754 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think many people are having
difficulty
understanding.

15:21.788 --> 15:23.623 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
ADM.

15:23.656 --> 15:27.927 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL MULLEN: Well, I think --
and I thought
General McMaster yesterday on
the Sunday show

15:27.960 --> 15:34.233 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
was excellent in sort of framing
it, that
there is going to be some of
both, clearly.

15:34.267 --> 15:39.405 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The priority, it seems to me, is
ISIS, and
that was used for justification
for this attack,

15:39.438 --> 15:46.879 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and in terms of supporting,
fighting ISIS,
and responding to the use of
chemical weapons.

15:46.913 --> 15:50.483 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
My own personal view is, I
think, you know,
in the long run -- and I don't
know how long

15:50.516 --> 15:56.055 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that is, but I think it's a
while -- that
Assad doesn't have much of a
future in that

15:56.088 --> 15:57.223 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
country.

15:57.256 --> 16:00.860 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I worry a little bit about --
quote -- "regime
change."

16:00.893 --> 16:04.096 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We haven't had a great deal of
success with
that in years.

16:04.130 --> 16:06.499 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's just really difficult.

16:06.532 --> 16:10.336 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That said, I think it's a strong
message,
at least from the Trump
administration, that

16:10.369 --> 16:14.574 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
we're not going to tolerate his
continuing
to certainly use these weapons.

16:14.607 --> 16:18.644 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And we will see where it goes
with respect
to the rest of Syria.

16:18.678 --> 16:20.479 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Russia.

16:20.513 --> 16:24.517 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The Associated Press is
reporting this afternoon
that, quoting a U.S. official as
saying they

16:24.550 --> 16:29.455 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
now have concluded that Russia
knew about
that chemical weapons attack
before it happened,

16:29.488 --> 16:33.926 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and they may even have gone in
and bombed
the location of the attack in
order to hide

16:33.960 --> 16:36.963 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
evidence that chemical weapons
were used.

16:36.996 --> 16:39.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If that's the case, what can the
U.S. do about
it?

16:39.899 --> 16:41.734 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
ADM.

16:41.767 --> 16:44.904 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL MULLEN: Well, I think
just the strike
itself, our strike itself was a
pretty strong

16:44.937 --> 16:53.679 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
signal to Russia in terms of
starting to draw
a line, if you will, in the sand
that there

16:53.713 --> 16:55.615 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
are limits, first of all.

16:55.648 --> 17:00.486 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Secondly, I think it undermines
the use of
chemical weapons, certain
weapons, certainly

17:00.519 --> 17:01.787 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
undermined Putin.

17:01.821 --> 17:05.625 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I know Secretary Tillerson is on
his way to
Moscow this week.

17:05.658 --> 17:10.696 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I expect -- I mean, I don't
know for a
fact, but I expect he will carry
a very strong

17:10.730 --> 17:13.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
message to Russia.

17:13.599 --> 17:19.906 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
McMaster yesterday talked about
he thought
it was important that Russia, in
fact, asked

17:19.939 --> 17:22.174 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
themselves what they're doing
and what they
hope to accomplish.

17:22.208 --> 17:29.081 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's been a considerable
amount of press
on deconflicting the U.S. and
Russia.

17:29.115 --> 17:34.153 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think that will continue,
even though
Russia has called it off, per
se.

17:34.186 --> 17:35.221 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: You think what
will continue?

17:35.254 --> 17:36.989 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
ADM.

17:37.023 --> 17:38.224 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL MULLEN: I think the
deconfliction
between the forces will
continue, although

17:38.257 --> 17:41.794 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
it's a pretty mixed battlefield
on the ground.

17:41.827 --> 17:46.599 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I suspect that the militaries
will figure
out a way to continue to do
that.

17:46.632 --> 17:53.572 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I think there's -- in the
long term, the
solution in Syria is politically
driven.

17:53.606 --> 17:55.408 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And I put it in two big pieces.

17:55.441 --> 17:57.176 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
One is, we have to stop the
killing.

17:57.209 --> 18:01.747 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the other is, we need to let
the refugees
-- we need to let Syrian
citizens go home.

18:01.781 --> 18:03.849 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And that was part
of my question.

18:03.883 --> 18:05.384 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Can it be done?

18:05.418 --> 18:09.422 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Can progress be made without
Russian participation
and Russian agreement?

18:09.455 --> 18:10.423 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
ADM.

18:10.456 --> 18:12.191 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MICHAEL MULLEN: No.

18:12.224 --> 18:14.427 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I have believed for years that
Russia was
going to be part of the solution
even before

18:14.460 --> 18:15.728 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
they went in.

18:15.761 --> 18:19.498 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Obviously, it became much more
evidence when
they did go in.

18:19.532 --> 18:24.971 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I don't think there is any
way that this
can be solved without the U.S.
and Russia

18:25.004 --> 18:28.841 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
getting together and figuring
out politically
what the solution is.

18:28.874 --> 18:32.845 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's going to be a need to
include other
political leaders in the region,
but certainly

18:32.878 --> 18:35.614 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the U.S. and Russia are the two
key ones.

18:35.648 --> 18:39.485 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Finally, Admiral
Mullen, North
Korea, right now, there is a
U.S. carrier

18:39.518 --> 18:45.925 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
group on the way to the Korean
Peninsula,
in the wake of North Korean
missile tests.

18:45.958 --> 18:46.926 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
ADM.

18:46.959 --> 18:48.694 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MICHAEL MULLEN: Yes.

18:48.728 --> 18:53.466 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And you were part
of a Council
on Foreign Relations report some
months ago

18:53.499 --> 18:58.304 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
saying that the next
administration had to
make getting China involved in
dealing with

18:58.337 --> 19:00.773 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
North Korea a priority.

19:00.806 --> 19:06.178 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Is it your sense that the
administration is
-- this administration is doing
that successfully?

19:06.212 --> 19:07.246 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Is that happening?

19:07.279 --> 19:09.215 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And do you think the Chinese can
make a difference?

19:09.248 --> 19:10.549 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
ADM.

19:10.583 --> 19:12.451 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MICHAEL MULLEN: I think the
Chinese can make
a huge difference.

19:12.485 --> 19:19.458 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think, if they don't, and
without them,
that the options are pretty
drastic and pretty

19:19.492 --> 19:21.627 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
bad pretty quickly.

19:21.660 --> 19:25.531 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
I do think the Trump
administration has taken
a more regular approach.

19:25.564 --> 19:29.902 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I see reported that there have
been National
Security Council meetings on
this, so there

19:29.935 --> 19:32.571 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
clearly is a planning process
which is going
on.

19:32.605 --> 19:37.109 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think the message from the
president, the
North Korean leadership, and the
rest of the

19:37.143 --> 19:41.547 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
world is that there are limits
on what he's
going to tolerate.

19:41.580 --> 19:46.685 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That was clearly priority
message in his meeting
with Xi Jinping, President Xi
Jinping, from

19:46.719 --> 19:49.255 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
China on Thursday.

19:49.288 --> 19:55.661 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
All of those steps, I think, are
positive
in, again, what is an enormously
complex problem.

19:55.694 --> 20:05.471 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He's got nuclear weapons that
are buried deeply,
that are very difficult to
impossible to hit.

20:05.504 --> 20:08.274 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He's emerging on more and more
capability.

20:08.307 --> 20:11.277 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the longer -- this is a very
tough solution
set, no matter what you do.

20:11.310 --> 20:16.982 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I do believe, the longer we
wait, the
more challenging the solution
set becomes.

20:17.016 --> 20:20.019 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: The longer the
U.S. waits to
do what?

20:20.052 --> 20:21.887 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
ADM.

20:21.921 --> 20:26.125 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL MULLEN: The longer we
wait to take
some sort of action, whether
it's negotiations

20:26.158 --> 20:32.064 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
or some kind of military
operation, depending
on what the president would
choose, the more

20:32.098 --> 20:37.570 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
difficult those solution sets
will become,
back to where you -- where they
started, from

20:37.603 --> 20:42.208 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the perspective of this solution
must go through
Beijing.

