32:39.024 --> 32:48.633 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: The continent of
Africa does
not now hold many
internationally well-known

32:48.667 --> 32:54.206 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
universities, but one man is
trying to change
that, a one-time Microsoft
executive who was

32:54.239 --> 32:56.942 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
educated in the United States,
Patrick Awuah.

32:56.975 --> 33:02.414 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
As special correspondent Fred de
Sam Lazaro
reports, as part of his Agents
for Change

33:02.447 --> 33:08.220 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
series, one special focus of
classes is to
teach Africa's next generation
of leaders

33:08.253 --> 33:10.021 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
about ethics.

33:10.055 --> 33:15.160 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: It looks
like a pretty
typical college campus, with
students working

33:15.193 --> 33:19.531 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in computer labs, studying at
the library,
or hanging out with friends.

33:19.564 --> 33:25.337 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But Ashesi University, in the
West African
nation of Ghana, has embarked on
an experiment

33:25.370 --> 33:30.242 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
which its founder hopes will
help start to
fundamentally change the entire
continent.

33:30.275 --> 33:35.881 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PATRICK AWUAH, President, Ashesi
University:
In the next three decades or so,
the population

33:35.914 --> 33:41.953 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of Africa is going to double,
and something
like 40 percent of working-age
people are

33:41.987 --> 33:43.955 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
going to be Africans in the
world.

33:43.989 --> 33:47.092 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
A lot of jobs need to be
created.

33:47.125 --> 33:50.996 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so we need to be educating
the next bench
in a way that they're going to
go create those

33:51.029 --> 33:53.164 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
jobs and create those
opportunities for people.

33:53.198 --> 33:57.369 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Patrick
Awuah was born
and raised in Ghana, but came to
the United

33:57.402 --> 34:02.941 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
States on scholarship to get an
undergraduate
degree in engineering from
Swarthmore and

34:02.974 --> 34:06.311 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
an MBA from the University of
California,
Berkeley.

34:06.344 --> 34:12.150 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He went on to become a program
manager at
Microsoft.

34:12.183 --> 34:17.055 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When he decided to return to his
homeland,
he assumed he would start a
software company,

34:17.088 --> 34:22.127 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but quickly realized the system
of higher
education was so poor, there
wasn't a competent

34:22.160 --> 34:24.396 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
work force to hire.

34:24.429 --> 34:28.833 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Experts say the problem with
education in
Africa is not so much that there
aren't enough

34:28.867 --> 34:33.939 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
institutions, but, rather, it's
in what students
are taught and how they're
taught it, with

34:33.972 --> 34:38.777 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
an emphasis much more on rote
learning and
memorization, much less on
critical thinking,

34:38.810 --> 34:40.779 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
on thinking for oneself.

34:40.812 --> 34:47.152 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PATRICK AWUAH: Under colonial
rule, the educational
system was really designed for
that, to educate

34:47.185 --> 34:51.189 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
people to follow instructions
and to do things
in a very consistent way.

34:51.222 --> 34:55.427 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: So, Awuah
decided he had
to start his own university.

34:55.460 --> 35:01.199 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
With money from American
friends, colleagues
and foundations, he raised $2.5
million to

35:01.232 --> 35:06.972 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
open a school with an initial
class of 30
freshman in 2002.

35:07.005 --> 35:10.875 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Ashesi has now grown to a campus
of nearly
800 students.

35:10.909 --> 35:16.982 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The guiding principle throughout
has been
a laser-like focus on three
principles: ethical

35:17.015 --> 35:19.150 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
leadership, innovation and
entrepreneurship.

35:19.184 --> 35:21.920 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PATRICK AWUAH: We need a lot of
innovation.

35:21.953 --> 35:25.056 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We need people who are trained
to drive that.

35:25.090 --> 35:30.228 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we need people who are going
to be working
on the government side, who are
going to create

35:30.261 --> 35:32.163 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
an enabling environment for
that.

35:32.197 --> 35:36.901 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Ghana, like
most countries
in Africa, has been plagued by
government-related

35:36.935 --> 35:38.970 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
corruption, which has hampered
job growth.

35:39.004 --> 35:44.843 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROSE DODD, Professor, Ashesi
University: For
the next three to four minutes,
come up with

35:44.876 --> 35:47.879 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a list of things that a brick
can be used
for.

35:47.912 --> 35:52.083 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Ashesi's
goal is to teach
students to fight against the
temptations

35:52.117 --> 35:55.053 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of corruption and think outside
the box.

35:55.086 --> 36:00.325 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It begins almost from the moment
a freshman
arrives on campus and takes a
mandatory course

36:00.358 --> 36:03.461 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
called Foundations of Design and
Entrepreneurship.

36:03.495 --> 36:05.230 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ROSE DODD: How many do you have?

36:05.263 --> 36:06.231 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
STUDENT: Twenty-nine.

36:06.264 --> 36:07.499 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ROSE DODD: Twenty-nine.

36:07.532 --> 36:09.334 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

36:09.367 --> 36:15.974 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PATRICK AWUAH: The instructor
says, you go
find a problem that you think is
worth solving,

36:16.007 --> 36:18.576 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and then come up with an answer
to problem.

36:18.610 --> 36:21.312 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's very open-ended and then...

36:21.346 --> 36:23.782 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: And scary in
part, I imagine.

36:23.815 --> 36:25.583 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
PATRICK AWUAH: Scary.

36:25.617 --> 36:32.757 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It feels like you have been
thrown into this
kind of weird world, where you
can't plant

36:32.791 --> 36:34.325 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
your feet on the ground.

36:34.359 --> 36:35.393 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Right?

36:35.427 --> 36:37.362 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's very different way of
approaching education.

36:37.395 --> 36:44.736 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROSE DODD: When you see a
problem, your first
human instinct is to think of
the first, easiest

36:44.769 --> 36:46.538 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
solution that comes to mind.

36:46.571 --> 36:50.708 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Professor
Rose Dodd, an
Ashesi alumna herself, says she
hopes the

36:50.742 --> 36:55.213 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
class will encourage her
students to take
on the entrenched establishments
in Ghana.

36:55.246 --> 36:57.082 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ROSE DODD: Don't be limited.

36:57.115 --> 37:01.686 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Don't feel that whatever the
system is limits
you.

37:01.719 --> 37:06.024 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Think about whatever else could
be and then
try it out.

37:06.057 --> 37:13.665 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think the goal, the end
goal should
be to make life better for
everybody around

37:13.698 --> 37:14.666 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
you.

37:14.699 --> 37:16.534 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MAN: Look at the question on the
board.

37:16.568 --> 37:21.172 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
FRED DE SAM LAZARO: Indeed, many
Ashesi graduates
have gone on to do some form of
public service,

37:21.206 --> 37:26.111 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
